U.S. Demand for Avocados and Conflict in Producing Countries¶

Why Avocados¶

Avocados are considered part of a loosely defined group of foods high in nutritional content known as Superfoods. According to Harvard Medical School there are many crops that qualify as superfoods that are grown domestically in the United States. Legumes, cruciferous vegetables, and whole grains are all examples of which the US produces plenty. The US as the top importer of Avocados globally (over $3 billion imported in 2020 alone) creates an incredible demand for Avocados.

Using data on production volume and import value I am going to investigate how change in demand affects major avocado producing regions.

For those more interested in visualizations and accompanying analysis than setup and cleaning, please see below:

Analysis

###############################################################
#### Formatting Functions ####
# Solution found at: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/61330427/set-y-axis-in-millions
def set_tick(num, pos):
    magnitude = 0
    while abs(num) >= 1000:
        magnitude += 1
        num /= 1000.0

    return "%.2f%s" % (num, ["", "K", "M", "B", "T", "P"][magnitude])

formatter = ticker.FuncFormatter(set_tick)

###############################################################
#### Helper Functions ####

# Helper function to reference current state of dataframe
# df will be the current state of the dataframe after manipulation
# var_name then can be used to refernce that
# Solution found at: https://youtu.be/zgbUk90aQ6A
def catch_state(df, var_name):
    globals()[var_name] = df

    return df

    ["Area"]
    .unique())

food = food.query('Area not in @mask')

Long Format¶

Before analyzing the data it needs to be pivoted to a wide format. Each of the columns representing values from 1961 - 2021 will be transformed to a single Years columns.

In [16]:
# Specify columns to pivot
melt_values = [f"Y{x}" for x in range(1961,2022)]

# Convert to long format
food_long = (pd.melt(food, id_vars = ["Area", "Item", "Element", "Unit"],
        value_vars = melt_values,
        var_name = "Year",
        value_name = "Quantity"))

# Convert Year column to numeric values
food_long["Year"] = pd.to_numeric(food_long["Year"].str.replace("Y", ""))
# Combine Element and Unit into single column
food_long["Element"] = food_long["Element"] + food_long["Unit"].apply(lambda row: f" ({row})")

Cleaning GDELT¶

Records of events from GDELT are mostly stored as individual tsv files for a single day. Getting data between 1990 and 2021 required downloading and parsing around 3000 individual files. An in depth examination of that process will be a separate breakdown.

GDELT encodes information about events using a system called CAMEO. The numbers represent a set of types of events. For example 01 : Make Public Statement includes 013: Make Optimistic Comment and 014: Consider Policy Option.

In [31]:

 '20': 'Use Unconventional Mass Violence',
 '--' : "Other"}

Analysis¶

First, has demand for avocados increased more relative to other crops the US imports? Import value, which represents the total amount dollars imported for a given year, will be used as a metric for demand.

In [33]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = SINGLE_PLOT_SIZE)
# Set Y axis format
ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)

(value.assign(Crop = np.where(value.Item == "Avocados", "Avocado", "Others (Mean val.)"))
    .groupby(["Year", "Crop"])
    .agg('mean')
    .reset_index()
    .pipe((sns.lineplot, 'data'), x = "Year", y = "Import Value ($)", 
          hue = "Crop")
)

ax.set_title("Annual Import Value in US $")

plt.show()

This plost shows the total annual import value of avocaods vs. the mean import value for all other crops in the data set. Clearly Avocados have seen a meteoric rise in the value relative to the rest of the crops that the US imports. The next question is where are Avocados primarily grown?

Comparing data directly from the Mexican agriculture bureau and the United Nations shows very similar trends. Relative to other crops in Mexico, Avocados are having more land dedicated to production while overall there appears to be a slight downward trend in land harvested by crop.

The mean for the top 100 crops by tonnage was used for the data from the Mexican government. The top crops from 2019 were used instead of 2020 because there was a sharp reduction in the number of unique crops included in the dataset in 2020.

GDELT¶

GDELT is a massive database updated daily that contains records on events that appear in news sources (online, print, tv, etc). GDELT encodes information about events using a system called Conflict and Mediation Event Observations (CAMEO). Broadly, each of the 20 parent CAMEO verbs fall into one of four categories:

  • 1 : Verbal Cooperation
  • 2 : Material Cooperation
  • 3 : Verbal Conflict
  • 4 : Material Conflict

The plot below shows the 20 verbs color coded by their corresponding Quad Class.

Around 2008 all four classes begin trending upward. Now, it's important to remember that this upward trend doesnt necessarily mean that Mexico suddenly started becoming more active as a country around 2008. Other possible reasons include:

  • More media attention paid to Mexico
  • Better Spanish language parsing from GDELT
  • More media coverage of all events in general

Import Value and Event Frequncy¶

Event frequency for an entire country is going to be incredibly noisy. It has a myriad of contributing factors, many having nothing to do with avocado production. In an attempt to reduce some of this noise, event frequency is going to be limited to the main production region in Mexico: Michoacn.

def quad_class_isolated(quad_class, ax):

      (gdelt_import_value.astype({"QuadClass_Eng" : "object"})
      .query('QuadClass_Eng == @quad_class')
      .groupby(["Year", "QuadClass_Eng"])
      .agg('sum')
      .reset_index()
      .pivot(index = "Year",
            columns = "QuadClass_Eng",
            values = "COUNT")
      .pct_change()
      .dropna()
      .rename_axis(None, axis = 1)
      .reset_index()
      .melt(id_vars = "Year",
            var_name = "QuadClass_Eng",
            value_name = "Event Freq. % Change")
      .pipe((sns.lineplot, 'data'), x = "Year", y = "Event Freq. % Change",
            color = "tab:blue",
            ax = ax)
      )
      ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.PercentFormatter(xmax = 1.0))
      ax.set_ylim([-1,6])
      ax.set_title(f"Event Class: {quad_class}")
      ax.grid(False)

      # Second axis of dual axis plot
      ax_value = ax.twinx()
      # Drop duplicated rows
      (gdelt_import_value.loc[~gdelt_import_value.duplicated(subset = ["Year", "Import Value ($)"])]
      .sort_values(by = "Year")
      .set_index("Year")
      ["Import Value ($)"]
      .pct_change()
      .reset_index()
      .dropna()
      .pipe((sns.lineplot, 'data'), x = "Year", y = "Import Value ($)",
            linestyle = '--',
            linewidth =  3.0,
            color = 'dimgray',
            ax = ax_value))
      ax_value.set(ylabel = "Import Value ($) % Change")

The plot above shows each of the individual Quad Classes plotted with the change in avocado import value. It does not appear that any of the classes associate more clearly with import value.

Conclusion¶

Viewing yearly data on import value for the United States does not immediately show a visible association between demand in the US and an increase in conflict in Michoacn.

However, absence of evidence is not necessarily evidence of absence. The information from the GDELT source is granular down to the daily level. Obtaining similarly detailed information on import price and performing some type of regression analysis could make assessing the degree and nature of the relationship more straightforward.
